span.font: A learned lookup table mapping token IDs (from the tokenizer) to token embeddings. Embeddings are high-dimensional dense vectors which the model learns to associate with token IDs during training. The embeddings attempt to capture each token's discrete meaning (which later layers will operate on and contextualize).How is this meaning represented in the embedding? A central tenet of mechanistic interpretability is that meaningful features are represented bydirections in the embedding space. However, the

div.span: individual components of the learned embeddings are not independently meaningful.

span.font: For GPT-2 Small, the embedding space is 768-dimensional. This

div.span: 31% of the model's total! (The ratio drops for larger models [link]).

Carries the input embeddings, plus the outputs from each sublayer of the model, to each subsequent sublayer.The residual stream is thecentral communication channel in a transformer; it doesn't do any processing itself and all layers communicate [only] through it. Each attention and MLP sublayer reads in the residual stream (via a linear projection), performs some computation, and then writes some result back to the residual stream (via element-wise addition).The only way the residual stream ismodified is by addition with these sublayer outputs; it is in essence a series of end-to-end skip connections.
This linear, additive structure has several important consequences. First, because addition preserves the gradient during back propagation, the gradient flows with full magnitude backwards through the residual stream to every layerduring training, preventing vanishing gradients and making it feasible to train very deep models.
Second, the residual connections help prevent theinput embeddings and early layer outputs from beingoverly degraded through repeated transformations. Information written by one layer can preserve through multiple layers without in the use of subspaces: earlier sublayers can communicate to specific later sublayers (or even specific later attention heads) bywriting todifferent subspacesof the residual stream.A single attention head might send different information to different layers by storing it in different subspaces.[Due to sparsity of high dimensional space?] it appears thatinformation persists in a subspace unless another layer actively deletes it
This persistence and the use of subspaces allows the model to optimize how information is pathed through the model. We can conceptualize transformers as implementing computational functions which correspond to particular paths: e.g., some function might gofrom an attention head in layer 2, through an MLP in layer 5, to an attention head in layer 8, and so on. [cite NN]
Each such path[circuit?] is free to use its own encoding.All of theseencoded messages from one layer to another to another arelayered on top of another in the residual stream. This makesthe residual stream itself not a particularly tractable target for interpretability work. Rather than analyze the residual stream vectors, it can be helpful to decompose the residual stream into all these different communication channels, corresponding to paths through the model.
[Further difficulty for interpreting the residual stream: The residual stream can be seen as the model's shared, working memory. It is the only way that information can move between layers, and so the model needs to find a way to store all relevant information in there (NN) Ergo, under high demand, and expect it to exhibit significant superposition.]

It is displayed here conceptually, with each embedding only interacting with itself and its preceding embeddings.

div.div: Transforms each input vector independently to have mean 0 and variance 1, then scales and shifts each component of the normalized vector bya learned scaling factor () and shifting factor (). (Each LayerNorm layer has a -length and which is applied component-wise.)

Purpose:The initial normalization promotes consistent distributions of input to a layer by reducing covariate shift (Ba et al., 2016),therebystabilizing gradients and speeding up training. The parameterized scale and shift then return some flexibility to the model, allowing it to optimize the transformation for each layer.

Implications:In the GPT-2 architecture, LayerNormmediates every read of the residual stream (en routeto each attention or MLP sublayer, and before Unembed). Because LayerNorm is anon-linear transformation,it complicates interpretability, which prominent researchershave expressed frustration about.

In principle, the non-linearity in LayerNorm can perform useful computation, and it can even work as a general-purpose activation function. In practice, within LLM architectures, it is an open question whether LayerNorm performs any meaningful computation or if it is merely an artifact of the training process.Attempts have been made to train more interpretable models without LayerNorm, and a recent preprintclaims to have removed GPT-2's LayerNorm layers with fine-tuning with only minor performance degradation, suggesting it does not play a crucial roleat inference time.

div.div: A learned lookup table mapping sequence positions to positional encodings. A challenge for the transformer architecture is that it is order invariant:although the token embeddings superficially appear to be stored in order, this ordering is not exposed to any of the model's computation. But for language, order matters.

div.style: text-align: left;
div.span: There are many approaches to adding position information (absolute or relative) to the token embeddings (or directly to the attention calculation). GPT-2 simply parameterizes it, allowing the model itself to figure out for itself how to represent sequence order. Each row of contains a learned time signal that is added to token embedding , thereby marking its position.
This means that the size of this matrix must be defined at training time, thereby fixing the maximum sequence length (context length) that the model can process: 1,024 for GPT-2.
